If you are putting in 14+ hour days *often*, there is a problem. It is very important that I do a good job at work, but other than the occasional &quot;Something&#039;s broken - it needs fixed at any cost.&quot; or &quot;we need help to get past this government audit.&quot; you should not be putting in hours like that. &lt;br /&gt;
Someone else&#039;s piss-poor project planning and chronic understaffing should not become your regular 70 hour work week.&lt;br /&gt;
It is difficult to stay on top of all of the new technology and tools, so as several others have stated, you need to specialize. (I know that this is not always posssible.)&lt;br /&gt;
It&#039;s great that you have found cool new things to learn - these are the things that keep us from burnout.&lt;br /&gt;
Best of luck!

I really like the honesty in your post, lots of people will never acknowledge that something is wrong or that they are trashing 2 days trying to find that answer to the problem.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I also find it helpful to split up task in more manageable chunks, what we do at my job is split it up in no more than what one workday (7 hours in my case) would be.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
You also need to be aware of people&#039;s skills around you, if someone knows a technology better than you then ask that person for help if you are dealing with that technology....there is no shame in doing that, nowadays more than ever nobody knows everything&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Just take a look at SQL Server, back in the 2000 and 7 days you might have known pretty much everything that there was to know.....these days that is just impossible with all the new things that they added like SSIS, SSRS, SSAS, Service Broker, SQLCLR, Extended Events, XML, Resource Governor, Powershell, VB, C#...and the list goes on and on.....
